# {{ .name }}

.NET transactional integration job. Polls JSON orders from a local inbound folder,
publishes them onto an in-memory Dapr pub/sub topic, processes each one through a
VETER pipeline, and writes the transformed result to a local outbound folder.

## Run

```bash
task run
```

This seeds `./local/storage/inbound` with the bundled sample order, starts the
local stack (grafana/otel-lgtm observability plus the Intropy Idempotency Service
and Business Incident Service — see `local/platform-services/`), and runs the job
once under Dapr. The runner picks up the file, publishes it via in-memory pub/sub
to topic `orders`, runs the send pipeline, writes the transformed JSON to
`./local/storage/outbound/<orderId>.json`, and deletes the source file.

{{- if not .empty }}
Run `task run` again with the same order and the send pipeline cancels at the
idempotency check instead of writing twice — the second run's trace shows the
check step cancelled and no downstream steps.
{{- end }}

Other tasks: `task build`, `task test`, `task clean` (remove `./local/storage`),
and `task services:down` (stop the local stack). See `Taskfile.yml`.

## Pipeline

**Receive** (per source file):

1. `Receiver` reads bytes from the inbound binding.
2. `Enqueuer` publishes the payload to `pubsub` / `orders`.
3. `Completer` deletes the source file.

**Send** (per pub/sub delivery):
{{- if .empty }}

1. `Deserializer` parses the JSON into `In`.
2. `Extractor` pass-through.
3. `Validator` enforces business rules.
4. `Transformer` maps `In` → `Out`.
5. `Serializer` serializes back to JSON.
6. `Sender` writes the JSON to the outbound binding.

Every step body throws `NotImplementedException` — this project was scaffolded
with empty bodies for a migration agent to fill in. When implementing, also wire
idempotency and business incidents (see `AGENTS.md`).
{{- else }}

1. `Deserializer` parses the JSON into `In` and stamps `order_id` / `processed_at`
   into the pipeline context.
2. Idempotency check — asks the Idempotency Service whether this `OrderId` /
   `OrderDate` combination was already processed; duplicates cancel the run.
3. `Extractor` pass-through.
4. `Validator` enforces required fields and basic business rules; failures are
   routed to the Business Incident Service.
5. `Transformer` maps `In` → `Out` and sums the line totals.
6. `Serializer` serializes back to JSON.
7. `Sender` writes the JSON to the outbound binding using `<orderId>.json`.

After a successful send the idempotency record is committed, so the next delivery
of the same order is recognised.
{{- end }}
